Tusk survives confidence vote Poland's government won a confidence vote in parliament on Wednesday. Reuters reported, according to Ritzau. At the start of June, the government supported the middle-seeking Rafal Trzakowski, who lost his pinch to Karol Nawroki, and it triggered the confidence vote. Donald Tusk, who is prime minister, held the vote to show that the government still has a majority.

POLAND PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION: HOW BETTORS 3X'D IN AN HOUR Karol Nawroki defeated Rafał Trzaskowski by 1.7%. The election saw meteoric swings on the day of the election, prompted by virtually nothing. Before a single vote was counted, Nawroki—a nationalist, patriotic conservative (who, again, ended up winning by over 1.5%)—saw his odds of winning drop below 15%. Meaning, if you bought Nawroki shares on the day of the election, you could have made a 550% return in just one hour! With $130M in liquidity, there was plenty of profit for those who predicted the right outcome. But why was the market so wrong? The fall of Nawroki to 15c is a concept insiders call momentum trading. Think about it this way: If you see an election expiring in 1 hour and one person has a 75% chance to win, your natural inclination is to toss money on the likely winner—since the market is usually right—and collect a quick profit. This then causes a snowball effect, which can become extreme, pushing a 60-40 race to 85-15. The crazy part? We gave Nawroki, not Trzaskowski a 60% chance to win the night before. He polled better in Eastern Poland than Duda did five years ago in his re-election. He underperformed in the cities but held strong in the suburbs. Despite Tusk’s liberal parliament and Romania’s liberal election result, there were clear signs of a conservative shift visible from the first round of the Polish election. Nawroki had an undeniable positioning advantage—one that even a solid candidate like Trzaskowski would find extremely difficult to overcome. Furthermore, Nawroki is himself an excellent candidate, capable of attention-grabbing moves while offering a clear vision and future for Poland. His victory was likely, even at 15c. Lesson learned? Election markets are often wrong.
